opulation Biology -- t20. Community Ecology -- t21. Network Science as a Framework for Bat Studies -- t22. Contemporary Biogeography -- tSection 6. Conservation -- t23. Challenges and Opportunities for the Conservation of Brazilian Phyllostomids -- t24. Threats, Status, and Conservation Perspectives for Leaf- Nosed Bats -- tContributors -- tSubject Index -- tTaxonomic Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith more than two hundred species distributed from California through Texas and across most of mainland Mexico, Central and South America, and islands in the Caribbean Sea, the Phyllostomidae bat family (American leaf-nosed bats) is one of the world’s most diverse mammalian families. From an insectivorous ancestor, species living today, over about 30 million years, have evolved a hyper-diverse range of diets, from blood or small vertebrates, to consuming nectar, pollen, and fruit. Phyllostomid plant-visiting species are responsible for pollinating more than five hundred species of neotropical shrubs, trees, vines, and epiphytes—many of which are economically and ecologically important—and they also disperse the seeds of at least another five hundred plant species. Fruit-eating and seed-dispersing members of this family thus play a crucial role in the regeneration of neotropical forests, and the fruit eaters are among the most abundant mammals in these habitats. Coauthored by leading experts in the field and synthesizing the latest advances in molecular biology and ecological methods, Phyllostomid Bats is the first overview in more than forty years of the evolution of the many morphological, behavioral, physiological, and ecological adaptations in this family. Featuring abundant illustrations as well as details on the current conservation status of phyllostomid species, it is both a comprehensive reference for these ecologically vital creatures and a fascinating exploration of the evolutionary process of adaptive radiation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhyllostomidae. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican leaf-nosed bats.  aPhyllostomidae.  aadaptive radiation.  abat behavior.  abat classification.  abat ecology.  abat evolution.1 aA. R. Mello, Marco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAdams, Danielle M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguiar, Ludmilla M. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguirre, Luis F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Justine J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmador, Lucila I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArévalo, R. Leticia Moyers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarclay, Robert M. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Enrico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinkløv, Signe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Gerald G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCirranello, Andrea L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz-Neto, Ariovaldo P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzaplewski, Nicolas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado-Jaramillo, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, M. May, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumont, Elizabeth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDávalos, Liliana M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov